The '''New Mexico Lobos football team''' is the intercollegiate [[college football|football]] team at the [[University of New Mexico]]. The Lobos compete as a member of the [[Mountain West Conference]]. They have a cumulative record of 449&ndash;513&ndash;31.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/mountainwest/new_mexico/coaching_records.php| title=New Mexico Coaching Records| publisher=www.cfbdatawarehouse.com| accessdate=2009-05-18}}</ref> Their official colors are cherry and silver. The Lobos' 30th head coach is [[Bob Davie (American football)|Bob Davie]], taking over for the former coach [[Mike Locksley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/7242433/bob-davie-new-mexico-lobos-coach|title=Bob Davie to be next New Mexico Lobos coach| publisher=www.espn.com| accessdate=2011-11-16}}</ref> Locksley, was fired in September, 2011, after a loss to Sam Houston State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koat.com/news/29297440/detail.html|title=Lobos Sack Coach Mike Locksley| publisher=www.koat.com| accessdate=2011-09-25}}</ref> Locksley had taken over in 2008, and went 2 and 28 in his tenure with the Lobos. Locksley's predecessor was [[Rocky Long]], who had guided the Lobos to five bowl games in seven seasons. The Lobos play their home games at [[University Stadium, Albuquerque|University Stadium]].
==Conference affiliation history== *1892&ndash;1930: Independent *1931&ndash;1951: [[Border Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] *1952&ndash;61: [[Mountain States Conference]] *1962&ndash;98: [[Western Athletic Conference]] *1999&ndash;present: [[Mountain West Conference]]
==Championships== ===Conference championships=== New Mexico has won four conference championships in two different conferences ([[List of Border Intercollegiate Athletic Association football champions|one in 1938 in the Border Conference]]), yet has not won a conference title in over 40 years.
